{{Culture of the United States}}
The '''literature of Tennessee''' in the United States includes fiction, poetry, and nonfiction. Representative authors include [[Shelby Foote]], [[Nikki Giovanni]], [[Alex Haley]], [[Mary Noailles Murfree]], [[John Crowe Ransom]], and [[Allen Tate]].{{sfn|Ensor|2009}}

==History==
{{Expand section|date=March 2017 }}
A [[Global spread of the printing press#North America|printing press]] began operating in [[Rogersville, Tennessee|Rogersville]] in 1791.<ref name=wroth1938>{{cite book |chapterurl=https://archive.org/stream/colonialprinter00wrot#page/15/mode/1up |chapter=Diffusion of Printing |title=The Colonial Printer |publisher=Southworth-Anthoensen Press |first=Lawrence C. |last=Wroth |author-link=Lawrence C. Wroth |edition=2nd revised |page=15 |date=1938 |oclc=2490245}}</ref>

In 1854 the [[Southern Methodist Publishing House|Methodist Publishing House]] relocated to Nashville from Philadelphia.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1986-05-28/business/fi-7970_1_publishing-house |title=Nashville: Publishing Bibles Is Big Business |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |first=Charles |last=Hillinger |date=May 28, 1986 |accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref><ref name="Blodgett1997">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CZLb2YQ4NCkC&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1 |title=Protestant Evangelical Literary Culture and Contemporary Society |publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group|Greenwood Press]] |location=Westport, Connecticut |first=Jan |last=Blodgett |series=Contributions to the Study of Religion |issue=51 |date=1997 |isbn=0-313-30395-9 |oclc=36147250}}</ref>

Mary Noalles Murfree (1850–1922) published under the pseudonym "Charles Egbert Craddock". Her ''In the Tennessee Mountains'' (1884) became a bestseller, featuring "stories of the Tennessee hill country".<ref name=Campbell2006>{{cite book |chapter=Regionalism and Local Color Fiction |title=American History Through Literature, 1870-1920 |publisher=Charles Scribner's Sons |location=Detroit, Michigan |first=Donna M. |last=Campbell |editor1-first=Tom |editor1-last=Quirk |editor2-first=Gary |editor2-last=Scharnhorst |volume=3 |date=2006 |isbn=978-0-684-31493-8 |oclc=62778245}}</ref>

In the 1920s the [[Fugitives (poets)|Fugitives]], a group of poets, was based at [[Vanderbilt University]] in Nashville. Also at Vanderbilt in the 1920s-1930s were the [[Southern Agrarians]], unofficially led by John Crowe Ransom.{{sfn|Young|1981}}

